properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued October 24 at 5:22PM CDT until October 24 at 5:30PM CDT by NWS San Angelo TX
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in San Angelo has issued a

* Tornado Warning for...
Southwestern Throckmorton County in west central Texas...

* Until 530 PM CDT.

* At 521 PM CDT, severe thunderstorms capable of producing both
tornadoes and extensive straight line wind damage were located 8
miles southwest of The Intersection Of Us-380 And Highway 222, or 9
miles southeast of Irby, moving northeast at 40 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed.
Damage to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree
damage is likely.

* This tornadic thunderstorm will remain over mainly rural areas of
southwestern Throckmorton County, including the following
locations... The Intersection Of Us-380 And Highway 222.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

properties.instruction:
Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

To report severe weather contact your nearest law enforcement agency.
They will send your report to the National Weather Service office in
San Angelo.

Continuous cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Move indoors immediately. Lightning is one of nature's leading
killers. Remember, if you can hear thunder, you are close enough to
be struck by lightning.

Torrential rainfall is occurring with this storm, and may lead to
flash flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded roadways.

properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued October 24 at 3:34AM PDT until October 24 at 11:00PM PDT by NWS Medford OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Moderate risk of sneaker waves expected. These are
waves that have an unusually higher run up on beaches when
compared to other observed waves.

* WHERE...Beaches along the Southern Oregon Coast, including the
beaches of Douglas, Coos, and Curry counties.

* WHEN...From 2 PM PDT this afternoon through 11 PM PDT this
evening.

* IMPACTS...Even during calm conditions, sneaker waves can sweep
up the beach without warning and knock unsuspecting people
over and pull them out to sea. Shock and hypothermia can occur
quickly in the cold Pacific waters. In addition, logs and
other debris can be lifted and carried by the waves, crushing
or entrapping unsuspecting victims underneath.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...South wind waves with building northwest
swells at 8 seconds, 12 seconds, and 18 seconds are expected.
The risk will be highest in the afternoon north of Cape Blanco,
and in the evening south of Cape Blanco.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr
properties.instruction:
Avoid climbing on rocks and jetties. Stay away from the ocean and
remain out of the water to avoid hazardous conditions.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued October 24 at 6:07PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
properties.description:
A broad tropical disturbance, JTWC Invest Area 93W, is centered
northwest of Koror, Palau and Yap Proper, near 10N135E. This broad
disturbance is generating showers and thunderstorms across much of
the Republic of Palau and western Yap State, including Ulithi and
Fais. Gusty winds associated with 93W are found well to the south of
the center, as well as along the eastern periphery, with sustained
winds between 20 and 25 knots.

93W is expected to stall in its current location for a couple days
with little forward motion away from Palau and Yap. As a result,
periods of showers, thunderstorms and strong, gusty winds will
persist over the region at least through midweek. Rainfall amounts of
5 to 7 inches are expected across Palau and Yap through Friday, with
locally heavier rainfall possible.

Gusty winds and elevated, choppy seas will make conditions hazardous
for small craft near Yap. Conditions could become hazardous across
Palau by midweek if winds increase further by Wednesday. Consider
postponing inter-island boat travel until conditions subside.

Residents of Palau and western Yap State should monitor local weather
forecasts and conditions closely the next couple days as 93W remains
in the vicinity. Be alert for ponding of water on roadways and
rapidly rising water in creeks and drainage areas. Stay up to date
with information from your Weather Service Offices in Palau and in
Yap, and for information from local emergency management offices. The
latest forecast can be found under WMO header FZPQ52 PGUM (AWIPS

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued October 23 at 3:50PM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
Confidence is increasing in the potential for accumulating snow
across the northern panhandle late Tuesday night into Wednesday.
The best chance for accumulating snow at sea level is over Haines
and Skagway. Along the Icy Strait corridor, including Hoonah,
Gustavus and Juneau, snow mixed with rain, but little to no
accumulation. As the storm system lifts northward Wednesday,
expect a changeover from a mix of rain and snow to rain for the
Icy Strait corridor early to mid Wednesday morning with Haines and
Skagway changing over mid to late afternoon. Higher elevations
along the Klondike highway could see more significant
accumulations through Wednesday night. Continue to check
weather.gov/juneau for the latest forecasts updates.
